[JENS NOTES]
I run afl++ with docker: 
docker pull aflplusplus/aflplusplus
docker run -ti -v ~/Documents/Uni/langsec/DD2525/Project:/src aflplusplus/aflplusplus

Second command will mount the folder Project as /src in the docker environment or whatever you call it

AFL use STDIN (which is what you use when writing in the terminal
after you launched the program, i.e NOT a launch argument)

The vuln.c code is vulnerabler to out-of-bound leaks. You can find the secret string
by typing (for me) 7 in the terminal, which is out of bounds for the array with words.

To make AFL++ detect the leak it can be compiled with: /src # afl-clang-fast -fsanitize=address vuln.c -o vuln
This instructs the compiler to add code that crashes the program when an out of bound thing occurs. 

I ran AFL with: afl-fuzz -i /src/vuln_seeds/ -o /src/results/ -- /src/vuln

The vuln_seeds, contains seeds, which in my case is just 5 files. First file contains a 0, second file a 1 and so on.
results is just where to store the result.

-- is what you add after all the setup stuff, everything after -- is your program. Like launch arguments and stuff, I think.

 
